message.content:
We have to determine the “Cost of Goods Sold” by extracting the cost associated with products that were sold. In our data the “Sale” transactions each include a field “cost_amount” in the last column. (That field represents for that sale the cost at which the product was “sold” – i.e. the cost of goods sold for that item.) Our approach is as follows:

1. From the table we select all lines where the “type” is “Sale” (each row records a sale). For each such row, we note the “cost_amount” value.
2. Then we add up these cost_amount values to obtain the overall cost of goods sold.

For example, the rows (with id and cost_amount) are as follows (the numbers come directly from the “cost_amount” column):

• Sale20240205072: 1,000.00  

When we add these values we may group them into categories:

• Nine transactions with 1,000.00 each contribute: 9 × 1,000 = 9,000.00  
• Eight transactions with 5,000.00 each contribute: 8 × 5,000 = 40,000.00  
• Twelve transactions with 20,000.00 each contribute: 12 × 20,000 = 240,000.00  
• One transaction with 60,000.00 is: 60,000.00  
• Fifteen transactions with 100,000.00 each contribute: 15 × 100,000 = 1,500,000.00

Now summing these subtotals:
 9,000.00 + 40,000.00 = 49,000.00  
 49,000.00 + 240,000.00 = 289,000.00  
 289,000.00 + 60,000.00 = 349,000.00  
 349,000.00 + 1,500,000.00 = 1,849,000.00

Thus, the final “Cost of Goods Sold” is 1,849,000.00.

Now we present the answer in the required JSON format:

    "Cost of Goods Sold": "1849000.00"
  }
}
